agape.example3: Maybe the same high levels of agape can be found throughout the “hospi-tality industry.”

deservedly.definition: (degree, manner) In a way or to a degree that is deserved or merited.
deservedly.example1: Circuit Judge William Bradford, after hearing a number of stories about Rush’s bravery and cures, wrote, “He is become the darling of the common people & his humane fortitude & exertions will render him deservedly dear.”
deservedly.example2: It reminded her of a certain abominable heresy, whose author was now deservedly languishing in the dungeons of the Consistorial Court.
deservedly.example3: Hombein’s and Unsoeld’s ascent was—and continues to be— deservedly hailed as one of the great feats in the annals of mountaineering.

wiped.example1: Some tar had oozed down the fenders, marring the blue color, and later, after Master went indoors, Ugwu carefully wiped it off, until the black glob covered only the headlights.
wiped.example2: He wiped his stinging eyes and turned back toward the stairs.
wiped.example3: I wiped my nose with my sleeve and started walking out the door.

esteemed.definition: To set a high value on; to regard with respect or reverence.
esteemed.example1: I imagined how esteemed I would be, as a newly cleansed vessel.
esteemed.example2: "I believe the cat to be alive. And what says my esteemed colleague?"
esteemed.example3: That was until Will Thompson’s grandfather, who was a member of the school’s board of trustees as well as an esteemed donor, got wind of the article.

asphyxiate.example1: They were going on a cruise because Kendra’s grandparents had asphyxiated.
asphyxiate.example2: This would be a fabulous time to asphyxiate on my own saliva, except my mouth has gone so dry, my tongue is turning to dust.
asphyxiate.example3: Poor engine hates it—coughing and spluttering the whole way—suppose I’m lucky I didn’t asphyxiate in the exhaust.

parkway.example1: The late-afternoon sun dances off the tops of the maple trees that are planted all along the parkway.
parkway.example2: It is no accident that the first highways in America were called parkways.
parkway.example3: We made it across and then knelt down in the knee-high grass beside the parkway.

crowned.definition: To place a crown on the head of.
crowned.example1: The last three pages of the album were devoted to boys in Greek tunics, crowned with laurel, playing among false Hellenic ruins, with chubby bottoms and heavy eyelashes—repulsive.
crowned.example2: If I had unhorsed Rhaegar and crowned Ashara queen of love and beauty, might she have looked to me instead of Stark?
crowned.example3: Once she took Celia to the foot of the hill crowned with the Church of Saint Lazarus.

moneylender.definition: A person who lends money and charges interest, especially one who is not part of the official financial industry
moneylender.example1: The brass bowls, Sass’s best sari, and her silver bangles were all carried to the moneylender in the village.
moneylender.example2: The Academy had taught us about rules the way a fundamentalist teaches the Bible in church, taking literally the injunctions about moneylenders and Armageddon and wives who existed to serve husbands.
moneylender.example3: Her voice sharp, Lupita scolded, “Salvador, she will need money to live on even after she pays the moneylender.”

unceremoniously.example1: The sailors, again with cloths tied around their mouths and noses, unceremoniously tossed the dead men overboard.
unceremoniously.example2: Afterward he took him directly to the station and unceremoniously loaded him onto the train.
unceremoniously.example3: They would summon the police, who would unceremoniously dump me in Dunning Asylum.

teleporting.definition: To travel, often instantaneously, from one point to another without physically crossing the distance between the two points.
teleporting.example1: I considered teleporting to Incipio before my “interview,” to buy a new skin for my avatar.
teleporting.example2: When I'm there by myself for too long, the house becomes some kind of time machine, teleporting me back three or four years, listening to my mom and dad fight and scream every night.
teleporting.example3: Sure, he did a lot of teleporting around the OASIS, completing quests and leveling up his avatar, but he didn’t actually know anything.

doubloon.example1: “You mean gold doubloons or those cheesy corn puffs?”
doubloon.example2: I look at the doubloon still gripped in my right hand.
doubloon.example3: Down in the grass, the dandelions shone like doubloons.

politico.example1: “They are more against the politicos,” Jack answered.
politico.example2: For the crowd of mostly Black politicos and journalists, belting out the “Family Affair” lyrics about not needing drama or “hateration” felt like a release.
politico.example3: Later, in Strathclyde, I was an unwilling audience for bent politicos who loved to boast as much as they loved power, money and being above the law.

unseat.example1: I remember being small and looking up, wondering if the rumble could unseat the heavens.
unseat.example2: It was a truly Aristotelian way of thinking—yet the void would soon unseat Aristotle once and for all.
unseat.example3: By themselves they had unseated the authority of a headmaster.

reassembling.example1: When the two monks finished cleaning the machine gun, Henry Dobbins began reassembling it, wiping off the excess oil, then he handed each of them a can of peaches and a chocolate bar.
reassembling.example2: Leo’s hands flew over the sphere, reassembling its missing pieces.
reassembling.example3: When I went to her chambers she had all the papers strewn over her tables, the ink scattering and reassembling, hollering their scandalous headlines.

wino.definition: A chronic or heavy drinker of cheap wine or other alcohol; a drunk or drunkard.
wino.example1: He brushed past the outstretched hand of a wino and caught up to his aunt and cousins.
wino.example2: She will play stick ball with the boys in the neighborhood and argue with the winos on the corner over who’s gonna win the next election.
wino.example3: It was a dilapidated housing project near St. Nicholas Avenue, with junkies and winos standing out front.
